Posts.Content: Aug 21, 2011 02:23AM kikiwiki wrote: I am under my parents insurance for less then 2 months. If it weren't for having it over the last year, I would never have been able to have all tests I have had done. My lumps did not show on US or mammo so I ended up having an MRI. That showed my lumps. If you do get diagnosed with cancer, most states are not legally allowed to drop you when you are too old for your parents insurance. Also there are health care advocate who will find state and federal programs to cover most if not all of your treatment if you cannot afford to pay and do not have insurance. Right now you need to focus on finding out what the problem is and got from there. If it cancer then will be able to deal with it. I had a friend diagnosed with stage 4 leukemia. He and his wife moved from Alaska to Seattle so he could get treatment from SCCA. Their health care advocate got him on disability, found housing for his wife and found programs that covered %100 of his medical bills. He was in the hospital for months and had to be on disability for several years. He only started working again last year. He is now cancer free! He is still on meds and will be for the rest of his life. One of his yearly tests is over 100,000 but the health care advocate found a program that pays for it! If you have cancer there are ways of dealing with it. For right now you need to go to the doctor and get your lump checked so you know how to proceed from here. Don't let money get in the way of your health. Your life is far too important!!!!
